<promed@promedmail.org>

[Black streaked dwarf and rice stripe viruses
---------------------------------------------
Black streaked dwarf disease of rice can be caused by _Rice black
streaked dwarf virus_ (RBSDV; genus _Fijivirus_), or the new, closely
related Southern rice black streaked dwarf virus reported from
northern Viet Nam and China. The viruses are spread by different
planthopper species. _Rice stripe virus_ (RSV; genus _Tenuivirus_) is
spreading in eastern Asia. An epidemic of its planthopper vector was
reported from northern Viet Nam in 2009 (ProMED-mail post
20090608.2118). Serious yield losses may be caused by these viruses
and their insect vectors. Disease management for rice viruses
includes cultural practices, vector control, and use of cultivars
with reduced sensitivity or resistance to the virus, the vector, or both.

Bacterial leaf streak
---------------------
Bacterial leaf streak of rice is caused by _Xanthomonas oryzae_ pv.
_oryzicola_ causes bacterial leaf streak of rice. It occurs in Asia
and West Africa and yield losses of up to 30 percent have been
recorded. Disease management includes phytosanitation (control of
weed and volunteer rice reservoir hosts, removal of contaminated
materials), cultural measures (optimal plant spacing and
fertilizers), and use of resistant crop varieties. Another strain of
the pathogen, _X. oryzae_ pv. _oryzae_, causes bacterial leaf blight,
which is also prevalent in the region.

Undiagnosed diseases
--------------------
The term 'black stunt' used above is not an official name of any rice
disease. A number of rice viruses can cause symptoms of
discolouration and stunting, but it is not clear which pathogen may
be referred to, or whether this is used as an alternative name for
black streaked dwarf.

The unidentified diseases in Hiep Hoa District described as viral in
item 1, and as "strange disease" in item 2, may refer to the same
problem. The symptom descriptions could apply to several viral but
also other pathogens, and a widespread undiagnosed disease was
reported from the area earlier in 2010 (ProMED-mail post
20100114.0162). In 2009, ragged stunt, rice stripe, and maize rough
dwarf viruses were reported from northern Viet Nam (ProMED-mail post
20090608.2118) and may have reappeared, but other diseases such as
bacterial leaf blight and fungal rice blast are also know to occur in
the region.

